The white wines of the Loire Valley are celebrated for their fresh, fruity flavor with their most notable characteristic—a sweet- ness held in check. Vouvray and Saumur are two most agreeable table wines, particularly at luncheon, and are becoming increasingly popular in America. The sparkling varieties have a delicacy which makes them analogous to Champagne, though for most cultivated tastes, they are a trifle too sweet.

Wines from Alsace and Lorraine are noteworthy and are com- monly grouped together as Alsatian wines. These generally re- semble the Rhine wines of Germany and make pleasant dry luncheon wines, especially with seafood.
